  "summary": "During a discussion regarding the ethics of euthanasia, Judith argues that mentally capable individuals have a responsibility to make decisions for those weakened by illness. She asserts that if a life is unhealthy or useless, it should be allowed to end painlessly, suggesting that only those who contribute to the community deserve to survive. Boyd Carrington agrees with this principle, while Norton challenges Judith, claiming she lacks the courage to act on such theories. Following the argument, Judith leaves the group in anger, followed by Boyd Cartwright.\n\nNorton approaches Hastings to express concern regarding Judith's frequent contact with Alton, a man with a bad reputation. Norton shares a story about an independent girl who committed suicide via a barbiturate overdose after being manipulated by Alton. This conversation leaves Hastings with a sense of foreboding; he becomes convinced that Alton is the murderer and fears that Judith is falling in love with him.\n\nLater, Boyd Carleton also advises Hastings to warn Judith about Alton. Struggling with indecision, Hastings finds Judith sitting alone and miserable in the rose garden. He approaches her and warns her that Alton is not worth her affection, noting that he is a married man and that their relationship will only lead to sadness, shame, and regret. Judith responds to his warning with a heartbreaking, sad smile.",
